Using the curvetun tunnel for browsing the web (example howto):

IPv4 example:

Server side:
  * You start curvetun server as usual and set up a NAT from eth0/curves0
    and enable IPv4 forwarding.
  * Your public IP on eth0, i.e. 1.2.3.4
  * Clocks periodically synced, i.e. ntpdate ntp.ubuntu.com pool.ntp.org

# ... start curvetun server ...
# ifconfig curves0 up
# ifconfig curves0 10.0.0.1/24
# echo 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
# iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE
# iptables -A FORWARD -i eth0 -o curves0 -m state --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT
# iptables -A FORWARD -i curves0 -o eth0 -j ACCEPT

Client side:
  * Your IP on eth0, i.e. 5.6.7.8
  * Clocks periodically synced, i.e. ntpdate ntp.ubuntu.com pool.ntp.org

# ... start curvetun client ...
# ... lookup your default gateway ...
  -> either stated in route, or
  -> traceroute google.ch and take the first IP entry
  -> default gw here i.e. 5.6.7.9
# ifconfig curvec0 up
# ifconfig curvec0 10.0.0.2/24
# route add -net 1.2.3.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 gw 5.6.7.9 dev eth0
# route add default gw 10.0.0.1
# route del default gw 5.6.7.9

... and there you go!

